[SPEAKER_06]: Seeing, no, you got your, you had your extra minute, Mike.

530
01:00:56,618 --> 01:00:57,298
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm sorry.

531
01:00:57,658 --> 01:00:58,959
[SPEAKER_06]: You go over on the first one.

532
01:01:01,600 --> 01:01:04,741
[SPEAKER_06]: If you'd gone 30 seconds, I would have given you 30 seconds, but you went 58 seconds.

533
01:01:04,781 --> 01:01:06,302
[SPEAKER_06]: No, you went 55 seconds.

534
01:01:07,322 --> 01:01:07,842
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry.

535
01:01:07,862 --> 01:01:10,703
[SPEAKER_06]: I, you know.

536
01:01:14,405 --> 01:01:17,026
[SPEAKER_06]: Any discussion, further discussion by members of the council?

537
01:01:20,067 --> 01:01:20,567
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Tseng.

538
01:01:23,067 --> 01:01:23,527
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

539
01:01:23,687 --> 01:01:31,228
[SPEAKER_19]: Just briefly, I'm going to be voting yes to defend the ordinance and I want to explain why very briefly.

540
01:01:32,049 --> 01:01:33,309
[SPEAKER_19]: This council didn't act alone.

541
01:01:33,689 --> 01:01:44,431
[SPEAKER_19]: We passed the values aligned local investments ordinance because more residents contacted us in support of it than almost any other measure we've taken up in recent memory.

542
01:01:45,151 --> 01:01:50,572
[SPEAKER_19]: Neighbors, community organizations, stakeholders across Medford were all brought together.

543
01:01:52,031 --> 01:01:55,512
[SPEAKER_19]: through a deliberative and inclusive process.

544
01:01:56,353 --> 01:01:59,714
[SPEAKER_19]: And that is how representative government is supposed to work.

545
01:02:01,034 --> 01:02:02,395
[SPEAKER_19]: We listen and we act.

546
01:02:03,075 --> 01:02:12,018
[SPEAKER_19]: The people of Medford made a choice about how their money is invested, ethically, with clear guidelines, in alignment with their values.

547
01:02:12,698 --> 01:02:13,899
[SPEAKER_19]: That's not a technicality.

548
01:02:14,039 --> 01:02:15,339
[SPEAKER_19]: It's not a policy preference.

549
01:02:15,639 --> 01:02:16,399
[SPEAKER_19]: That's democracy.

550
01:02:19,671 --> 01:02:24,953
[SPEAKER_19]: Now, a few individuals backed by outside interest groups are asking a court to undo that.

551
01:02:26,493 --> 01:02:27,894
[SPEAKER_19]: I can't vote to let that stand.

552
01:02:28,394 --> 01:02:33,555
[SPEAKER_19]: If we decline to defend this ordinance, we're not being cautious, we're surrendering.

553
01:02:34,455 --> 01:02:44,439
[SPEAKER_19]: And we're telling residents who showed up, who called, who wrote to us, that their voice only matters when someone with resources decides to challenge it.

554
01:02:45,599 --> 01:02:48,960
[SPEAKER_19]: Medford's residents chose to be in charge of their community's money,

555
01:02:50,118 --> 01:02:52,560
[SPEAKER_19]: They asked us to make that choice real.

556
01:02:53,781 --> 01:02:57,164
[SPEAKER_19]: My job today and what I see as our job today is to stand behind them.

557
01:02:57,805 --> 01:02:59,746
[SPEAKER_19]: So that's why I support it.

558
01:03:00,146 --> 01:03:06,952
[SPEAKER_19]: I respect, you know, my colleague who will probably vote another way tonight, but that is my view on the issue.

559
01:03:10,655 --> 01:03:11,516
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councilor Tseng.

560
01:03:13,318 --> 01:03:13,558
[SPEAKER_06]: You know,

561
01:03:17,101 --> 01:03:34,912
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the raising of the mayor's legal messes and the fiscal situation of the city are largely red herrings to the fundamental question here, which is, do you give the mayor a second veto when her first veto is overridden?

562
01:03:35,693 --> 01:03:41,977
[SPEAKER_06]: And do you give a couple of opponents a litigation veto because they don't like the way the vote went?

563
01:03:43,254 --> 01:03:48,798
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, whether that's this ordinance or any other ordinance, it went through the democratic process.

564
01:03:49,078 --> 01:04:04,550
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't believe it's wasteful to protect the democratic process from being undermined by any litigant on any subject who wants to change an outcome to satisfy their personal opinion over a decision made by a democratically elected government through all of the necessary procedural requirements of the law.

565
01:04:06,031 --> 01:04:08,613
[SPEAKER_06]: I think we have a strong legal argument against the litigation.

566
01:04:10,351 --> 01:04:14,414
[SPEAKER_06]: And, you know, the issues are just really not zero sum in my eyes, right?

567
01:04:14,514 --> 01:04:22,900
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, yeah, there's a bunch of lawsuits that the mayor has been fighting tooth and nail for years that we lose at the end of the day.

568
01:04:23,060 --> 01:04:24,161
[SPEAKER_06]: What are the legal fees on that?

569
01:04:24,281 --> 01:04:25,381
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to know the answer to that.

570
01:04:25,902 --> 01:04:34,428
[SPEAKER_06]: There are three or four developments in the city that could be have been built, finished being built two years ago that would have brought a new revenue that would adjust the fiscal picture that the city is facing.

571
01:04:35,969 --> 01:04:38,070
[SPEAKER_06]: Those are just fundamentally different issues to we,

572
01:04:40,272 --> 01:04:48,775
[SPEAKER_06]: went through an ordinance process, we approved it, the mayor vetoed, we overrode that veto, and it's the law.

573
01:04:49,755 --> 01:05:02,980
[SPEAKER_06]: We did what we thought was right, we're defending doing something that we thought was right, and just because the mayor lost, and just because two people who've decided to sue lost, they don't get a second veto unless the mayor wants to give it to them.

574
01:05:03,461 --> 01:05:07,342
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think there's a real question, going back to the argument about legal counsel here,

575
01:05:08,847 --> 01:05:13,155
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't believe this council felt we were being effectively represented when this ordinance was drafted.

576
01:05:14,297 --> 01:05:18,704
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think this council continues to have concerns about whether we're being effectively represented in the defense.

577
01:05:19,630 --> 01:05:23,693
[SPEAKER_06]: Not just of this, but we heard it on the ordinance we discussed for an hour and a half before this.

578
01:05:23,733 --> 01:05:27,695
[SPEAKER_06]: We've been hearing it on the legal arguments and the legal settlements.

579
01:05:27,715 --> 01:05:36,040
[SPEAKER_06]: We've been hearing it on case after case after case, where the mayor is fighting tooth and nail against claims that we eventually lose.

580
01:05:36,181 --> 01:05:39,182
[SPEAKER_06]: And then the taxpayers pay not only the claimants, but they pay the legal fees.

581
01:05:39,743 --> 01:05:47,228
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a completely different, completely different thing for us to say, we believe we have a strong legal footing.

582
01:05:48,112 --> 01:05:54,433
[SPEAKER_06]: There are a number of folks who I've spoken to who'd be willing to represent this city for little to no cost.

583
01:05:55,074 --> 01:05:57,314
[SPEAKER_06]: And then the mayor came back and said, you have to ask me for $75,000.

584
01:05:57,354 --> 01:06:01,035
[SPEAKER_06]: So okay, we'll ask.

585
01:06:01,775 --> 01:06:02,875
[SPEAKER_06]: We think you should defend this.

586
01:06:02,935 --> 01:06:05,936
[SPEAKER_06]: We do not think the city should default on this litigation.

587
01:06:05,996 --> 01:06:09,537
[SPEAKER_06]: We do not think that the city should not defend the law of the city of Medford.

588
01:06:10,477 --> 01:06:13,958
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that's a pretty basic position that anyone would take.

589
01:06:15,669 --> 01:06:21,622
[SPEAKER_06]: And if there was another law that I didn't agree with, I wouldn't support the mayor not defending it.

590
01:06:24,140 --> 01:06:26,901
[SPEAKER_06]: I just wouldn't support that, because I think it weakens the city.

591
01:06:26,921 --> 01:06:35,885
[SPEAKER_06]: I would certainly advocate for the legislature to change that law, or I would have worked to try to get the law to be different.

592
01:06:36,105 --> 01:06:38,326
[SPEAKER_06]: Maybe if I were the mayor, I would have vetoed the law.

593
01:06:38,406 --> 01:06:47,189
[SPEAKER_06]: But if I lost, I would defend the law of the city of Medford against a litigant who doesn't have a strong case and is trying to undermine the democratic process.

594
01:06:47,509 --> 01:06:48,550
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's what we're asking for.

595
01:06:49,490 --> 01:06:51,791
[SPEAKER_06]: And in addition to all of that, I do support this.

596
01:06:51,831 --> 01:06:52,771
[SPEAKER_06]: I think it's a good thing.

597
01:06:52,791 --> 01:07:00,393
[SPEAKER_06]: I think a lot of people think it's a good thing and really stands very strongly on legal grounds in my opinion.

598
01:07:00,533 --> 01:07:09,396
[SPEAKER_06]: So we are certainly open to council talking to the other party to see what kind of arrangement they'd like to come to.

599
01:07:09,476 --> 01:07:12,337
[SPEAKER_06]: I know that was mentioned, whether or not we'd accept that.

600
01:07:12,980 --> 01:07:17,844
[SPEAKER_06]: We have to discuss that, but no, we're not saying don't talk to them, defend a tooth and nail.

601
01:07:17,904 --> 01:07:21,427
[SPEAKER_06]: That's actually what the mayor's saying on every single time a union files a grievance.

602
01:07:22,768 --> 01:07:24,290
[SPEAKER_06]: We want all the information that we can get.

603
01:07:25,309 --> 01:07:34,211
[SPEAKER_06]: We want all the information that we can get, and we also want the mayor to at least test the case of our opponents.

604
01:07:34,911 --> 01:07:36,071
[SPEAKER_06]: At least, don't just give up.

605
01:07:36,331 --> 01:07:38,932
[SPEAKER_06]: Don't surrender before the first shot has been fired.

606
01:07:39,932 --> 01:07:40,832
[SPEAKER_06]: Their case is weak.

607
01:07:41,513 --> 01:07:43,313
[SPEAKER_06]: Why would we give up without at least testing that?

608
01:07:44,173 --> 01:07:47,354
[SPEAKER_06]: If it ends up moving towards the settlement approach,

609
01:07:48,597 --> 01:07:50,380
[SPEAKER_06]: That's a discussion for us to have down the road.

610
01:07:50,901 --> 01:07:55,929
[SPEAKER_06]: But the mayor is saying for any of those things to happen, we have to put this ordinance, this resolution forward.

611
01:07:56,049 --> 01:07:58,453
[SPEAKER_06]: So I'm happy to do that.

612
01:07:59,614 --> 01:08:00,275
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Callahan.

613
01:08:02,259 --> 01:08:02,479
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

614
01:08:05,390 --> 01:08:10,691
[SPEAKER_08]: For many years, for a couple of decades, I was completely uninvolved in politics.

615
01:08:10,951 --> 01:08:12,832
[SPEAKER_08]: I never voted in a city election.

616
01:08:12,872 --> 01:08:14,372
[SPEAKER_08]: I never voted in a state election.

617
01:08:14,412 --> 01:08:15,872
[SPEAKER_08]: I never voted in a primary.

618
01:08:16,012 --> 01:08:19,553
[SPEAKER_08]: It didn't seem to really have anything to do with my life.

619
01:08:20,374 --> 01:08:35,017
[SPEAKER_08]: And then in 2016, I got really intrigued by a candidate who talked about something that I felt deeply in my bones, which is that we are in a battle.

620
01:08:35,737 --> 01:08:41,780
[SPEAKER_08]: between moneyed interests and everybody else about who controlled our government.

621
01:08:42,700 --> 01:08:43,681
[SPEAKER_08]: It happened to be Bernie Sanders.

622
01:08:43,701 --> 01:08:50,204
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't think you have to like him or even know who he is to have that kind of understanding.

623
01:08:50,224 --> 01:08:56,447
[SPEAKER_08]: And I think many people who didn't even think that in 2016 have now come to think that.

624
01:08:57,647 --> 01:09:02,950
[SPEAKER_08]: And I just wanna say, this here that we are talking about right now,

625
01:09:04,355 --> 01:09:05,215
[SPEAKER_08]: This is the battle.

626
01:09:06,956 --> 01:09:26,301
[SPEAKER_08]: This is the battle between us having a democracy that represents people, the people who actually live here, and us having a group of people who are controlled by moneyed interests, whether they are corporations or billionaires or what have you.

627
01:09:28,562 --> 01:09:30,082
[SPEAKER_08]: This is what we are talking about.

628
01:09:31,882 --> 01:09:33,763
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is why I am going to vote

629
01:09:34,645 --> 01:09:51,228
[SPEAKER_08]: in favor of the city defending the ordinance that was clearly voted by a large majority of the duly elected city council and very much supported by the residents.

630
01:09:51,488 --> 01:09:51,768
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you.

631
01:09:54,348 --> 01:09:54,748
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

632
